the shape of the image is:  (768, 1024, 3)

Make note of the fact that the first two dimensions are ROWS x COLUMNS. When indexing into this array, you'll need to use this convention, as opposed to thinking of X and Y position (which would actually be column and row, respectively).

Convert the image to grayscale instead

To start with, look at any (or all) of the color channels individually. Are they all the same?

In [7]:
# answer 1
from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable

fig,ax=plt.subplots(1,3,figsize=(12,3))
colors = ['Red','Green','Blue']

for ii in range(3):
    im = ax[ii].imshow(face[:,:,ii],cmap='gray')
    ax[ii].set_title('intensity in '+colors[ii])
     
    # all this junk is necessary to make a separate colorbar for each image
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax[ii])
    cax = divider.append_axes("right", size="20%", pad=0.05)
    cbar = plt.colorbar(im, cax = cax, extendfrac=20,label='pixel intensity',orientation='vertical')
    cbar.draw_all()

fig.tight_layout()

To properly convert the color channels to gray (luminance), you need to account for our visual system's sensitivity to each individual color: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grayscale#Converting_color_to_grayscale. Try writing a function to do this, then applying it to the image.

In [8]:
#answer
def rgb2gray(im):
    gray = 0.2989*im[:,:,0] + 0.5870*im[:,:,1] + 0.1140*im[:,:,2]
    return gray
In [9]:

fig,ax=plt.subplots()
im = ax.imshow(gray_face,cmap='gray')

In the grayscale image, choose a threshold, then make all values above that threshold white and all values below that threshold black

**Bonus exercise: Use a sliderbar widget to make the threshold dynamically adjustable:**

see: http://ipywidgets.readthedocs.io/en/latest/examples/Using%20Interact.html

In [12]:
# basic answer
gray_face_thresholded = gray_face.copy() #make a copy of the data so you don't affect the original image

threshold = 150
gray_face_thresholded[gray_face_thresholded<=threshold] = 0
gray_face_thresholded[gray_face_thresholded>threshold] = 1

fig,ax=plt.subplots()

ax.imshow(gray_face_thresholded,cmap='gray')
Out[12]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x11128af10>
In [13]:
# Answer with slider bar
# have to run 'pip install ipywidgets' from the command line first
from ipywidgets import interact
@interact
def show_thresholded(threshold=(0,255,1)):
    gray_face_thresholded = gray_face.copy() #make a copy of the data so you don't affect the original image

    gray_face_thresholded[gray_face_thresholded<=threshold] = 0
    gray_face_thresholded[gray_face_thresholded>threshold] = 1

    fig,ax=plt.subplots()

    ax.imshow(gray_face_thresholded,cmap='gray')

Try making plots of intensity values for an x,y cross section through the image

In [14]:
#answer
import matplotlib.gridspec as gridspec

x_val = 425
y_val = 850

fig=plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
# Create grispec object and define each subplot
gs = gridspec.GridSpec(2, 2, width_ratios=[3, 1],height_ratios=[1,3])
ax_image = plt.subplot(gs[1, 0]) # Bottom, span entire width

ax_top = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, 0], sharex=ax_image)
ax_right = fig.add_subplot(gs[1,1], sharey=ax_image)

#show the image
ax_image.imshow(face,cmap='gray')

#make the line plot at top
ax_top.plot(face[x_val,:,0],color='red')
ax_top.plot(face[x_val,:,1],color='green')
ax_top.plot(face[x_val,:,2],color='blue')
ax_top.set_xlim(0,gray_face.shape[1])
ax_top.set_title('RGB Values through horizontal cross section')
# ax_top.set_xticklabels([])
ax_image.plot(np.arange(0,face.shape[1]),x_val*np.ones(face.shape[1]),color='white')


#make the line plot at right
ax_right.plot(face[:,y_val,0],np.arange(0,face.shape[0]),color='red')
ax_right.plot(face[:,y_val,1],np.arange(0,face.shape[0]),color='green')
ax_right.plot(face[:,y_val,2],np.arange(0,face.shape[0]),color='blue')
ax_right.invert_yaxis()
ax_right.set_title('RGB Values\nthrough vertical\n cross section')
ax_right.set_ylim(gray_face.shape[0],0)
# ax_top.set_ylim(0,gray_face.shape[0])
ax_image.plot(y_val*np.ones(gray_face.shape[0]),np.arange(0,gray_face.shape[0]),color='white')

#ensure that the image is framed properly
ax_image.set_xlim(0,gray_face.shape[1])
ax_image.set_ylim(gray_face.shape[0],0)

fig.tight_layout()
